ecent_six.canonical_claim_0411", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0436", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0437", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0438", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0439", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0440", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0449", "naval_recent_six.canonical_claim_0450"], "first_seen_at": "2026-05-27", "last_seen_at": "2026-06-01", "position_id": "naval_recent_six.position.guillermo_rauch", "representative_claims": ["Even if there’s potential for extra optimization, there’s still cooperation-at-large-scale value of saying “we’re both depending on Postgres 13.2.”\n\nThe category of infrastructure software and building blocks these agents are going to use is—obviously in bias, this is what we’re building—extremely valuable.", "The job of the engineer being something where you just show up to work, you ship the output directly, and everything inside the company was—“how good is person A at shipping output B?”\n\nAnd now what’s happening is, the way I’m judging you as an engineer is, “are you producing the factory that will produce multiplicative outputs B through Z?”\n\nThat’s a pretty significant change.", "When Max was talking about this potentially being a good thing — that we have all this regulation — my head went to: the thing that makes agents successful is humans or other agents setting up the right testing guardrails.", "And obviously, sometimes they bullshit, which is hilarious—it tells you “this is going to take three weeks” and “this many tokens.” It makes really bad predictions.", "The human is the one starting to get the instructions back: “Go get me this API key, because it’s something only you can do.”\n\nOr “Get me this amount of capital for my next set of investments.” You just watch.", "A really proficient engineering leader has been quote-unquote vibe coding through people on Slack or one-on-ones—you’re transmitting your will, your intent, your experience, and letting others run with it.", "I’m signing off on understanding the consequences.” Or, “I wrote the test harness, the simulations, the proofs, the type-checkers—even without reading this, I have confidence I can sign off that it’ll be safe in production.”\n\nThere’s a world in which we embrace that everything is going to be spaghetti code we don’t fully understand, but we write the evaluators that give us confidence, and we rely on people—the infrastructure production engineers—to say, “Okay, I’m fine sending this into prod.” Someone is going to get paged if your systems go down.", "As long as passing them doesn’t incur contradictions, and the regulations are actually reasonable, they’re an awesome guardrail."], "source_family_ids": ["naval_frontier_founders_industrial_2026"], "speaker": "Guillermo Rauch", "speaker_status": "source_provided", "themes": ["ai_capability_and_agi", "software_production", "hardware_engineering", "time_compute_substitution", "ai_coding_agents", "geopolitics", "future_of_work", "token_economics", "truth_and_credibility", "institutional_change", "recruiting_and_culture", "regulation", "startup_organization", "leverage", "manufacturing", "vertical_integration", "persuasion_and_sales"]}
